      <div class="hpmeta">
         <div class="text">
            <div id="hp01_007" class="hp"><span class="number">HP 1.7</span><div class="versdev">
                  <p class="hpvers"> <mark>काणेरी</mark> <mark>पूज्य</mark>पादश्च <mark>नित्यनाथो</mark> निरञ्जनः ।</p>
                  <p class="hpvers"> <mark>कपाली</mark> बिन्दुनाथश्च काक<mark>चण्डीश्वराह्वयः</mark> ॥</p> 
                  </div>
               <div class="versltn">
                  <p class="hpvers"> <mark>kāṇerī</mark> <mark>pūjya</mark>pādaś ca <mark>nityanātho</mark> nirañjanaḥ /</p>
                  <p class="hpvers"> <mark>kapālī</mark> bindunāthaś ca kāka<mark>caṇḍīśvarāhvayaḥ</mark> //</p> 
                  </div>
            </div>
            <div class="translation"> Kāṇerī, Pūjyapāda, Nityanātha, Nirañjana, Kapālī, Bindunātha, and the one named Kākacaṇḍīśvara.
               </div>
            <details class="philcomm-d">
               <summary>Philological Commentary</summary>
               <div class="philcomm"> It is possible that <i>pūjyapāda</i> could be a respectful affix to the name Kāṇerī. The variant <i>dhvaninātha</i> may have resulted from a transposition of the first two syllables of <i>nityanātha</i>. The α group supports <i>kākacaṇḍīśvaro gayaḥ</i> but we have not been able to find evidence for a Siddha called Gaya. </div>
            </details>
         </div>
         <div class="crit">
            <div class="apparatus">
               <h3>Readings</h3>
