   <div class="main">
      <div class="hpmeta">
         <div class="text">
            <div id="hp01_024" class="hp"><span class="number">HP 1.24</span><div class="versdev">
                  <p class="hpvers"> <mark>कुक्कुटा</mark>सन<mark>बन्धस्थो</mark>दोर्भ्यां <mark>संबध्य</mark> <mark>कन्धराम्</mark> ।</p>
                  <p class="hpvers"> <mark>शेते</mark> <mark>कूर्मव</mark><mark>दुत्तान</mark> एतदुत्तान<mark>कूर्मकम्</mark> ॥</p> 
                  </div>
               <div class="versltn">
                  <p class="hpvers"> <mark>kukkuṭā</mark>sana<mark>bandhastho</mark>dorbhyāṃ <mark>saṃbadhya</mark> <mark>kandharām</mark> /</p>
                  <p class="hpvers"> <mark>śete</mark> <mark>kūrmava</mark><mark>d uttāna</mark> etad uttāna<mark>kūrmakam</mark> //</p> 
                  </div>
            </div>
            <div class="translation"> While in the wild cock pose, [the yogi] binds the neck with the hands and lies [on
               his back] upturned like a tortoise. This is the upturned tortoise (<i>uttānakūrmaka</i>). </div>
            <details class="philcomm-d">
               <summary>Philological Commentary</summary>
               <div class="philcomm"> The oldest dated manuscript, η1, has <i>kukkuṭāsanavat kṛtvā</i>, which is a simpler alternative to the widely attested reading <i>kukkuṭāsanabandhasthaḥ</i> (including α2 and α3), which we have accepted. Since there is no known source for this verse other than
                  the <i>Haṭhapradīpikā</i>, it appears that the reading of η1 was an isolated attempt to simplify the syntax. </div>
            </details>
         </div>
         <div class="crit">
            <div class="apparatus">
               <h3>Readings</h3>
