   <div class="main">
      <div class="hpmeta">
         <div class="text">
            <div id="hp01_050" class="hp"><span class="number">HP 1.50</span><div class="versdev">
                  <p class="avataranika"> <mark>अथ सिंहासनम्</mark> । </p>
                  <p class="hpvers"> गुल्फौ <mark>च</mark> वृषणस्याधः <mark>सीवन्याः</mark> पार्श्वयोः क्षिपेत् ।</p>
                  <p class="hpvers"> <mark>दक्षिणे</mark> सव्यगुल्फं <mark>तु</mark> <mark>दक्षगुल्फं</mark> <mark>तु</mark> <mark>सव्यके</mark> ॥ 
                     </p> 
                  </div>
               <div class="versltn">
                  <p class="avataranika"> <mark>atha siṃhāsanam</mark> / </p>
                  <p class="hpvers"> gulphau <mark>ca</mark> vṛṣaṇasyādhaḥ <mark>sīvanyāḥ</mark> pārśvayoḥ kṣipet /</p>
                  <p class="hpvers"> <mark>dakṣiṇe</mark> savyagulphaṃ <mark>tu</mark> <mark>dakṣagulphaṃ</mark> <mark>tu</mark> <mark>savyake</mark> // 
                     </p> 
                  </div>
            </div>
            <div class="translation"> Now, the lion’s pose (<i>siṃhāsana</i>). [The yogi] should put both ankles at the sides of the perineal seam below the scrotum.
               He should place the left ankle on right, the right ankle on the left and both hands
               on the knees, spread his fingers, open his mouth and gaze in deep concentration at
               the tip of his nose. This is the lion’s pose, which is always honoured by yogis. It
               causes the three locks to arise together and is the best of [all] postures. </div>
         </div>
         <div class="crit">
            <div class="apparatus">
