   </div> 
   </div><div id="hp2">
   <div class="main">
      <div class="hpmeta">
         <div class="text">
            <div id="hp02_001" class="hp"><span class="number">HP 2.1</span><div class="versdev">
                  <p class="hpvers"> <mark>अथासने</mark> <mark>दृढे</mark> योगी <mark>वशी</mark> <mark>हितमिताशनः</mark> ।</p>
                  <p class="hpvers"> <mark>गुरूपदिष्ट</mark>मार्गेण <mark>प्राणायामं</mark> <mark>समभ्यसेत्</mark> ॥</p> 
                  </div>
               <div class="versltn">
                  <p class="hpvers"> <mark>athāsane</mark> <mark>dṛḍhe</mark> yogī <mark>vaśī</mark> <mark>hitamitāśanaḥ</mark> /</p>
                  <p class="hpvers"> <mark>gurūpadiṣṭa</mark>mārgeṇa <mark>prāṇāyāmaṃ</mark> <mark>samabhyaset</mark> //</p> 
                  </div>
            </div>
            <div class="translation"> Now, when [his] posture is steady, the disciplined yogi whose diet is good and measured
               should practise breath control in the way taught by [his] teacher. </div>
            <details class="philcomm-d">
               <summary>Philological Commentary</summary>
               <div class="philcomm"> The <i>Jyotsnā</i> (2.1) has the plural <i>prāṇāyāmān</i>, which is supported by some manuscripts of the β, γ and ε groups. The plural is possible
                  here as it could refer to the different techniques of retention (<i>kumbhaka</i>) taught later in the chapter. This is how Brahmānanda understands it (<i>prāṇāyāmān vakṣyamāṇān</i>). The variation between singular and plural recurs through this chapter, and we have
                  followed the α readings, which make good sense. In this case, since the verse is introducing
                  the topic of breath control, the more general sense of the singular is appropriate.
                  </div>
            </details>
         </div>
         <div class="crit">
            <div class="apparatus">
               <h3>Readings</h3>
               <div class="app"><span class="lem">athāsane</span> (<span class="siglum" title="cett. ceteri">cett.</span>) ] athāsāna (<span class="siglum" title="γ1 NGMPP G 25-2 γ1ac γ1pc">γ<sub>1</sub></span>), athābhyāsena (<span class="siglum" title="δ3 Lalchand M-6494">δ<sub>3</sub></span>), haṭhāsane (<span class="siglum" title="η1 Sampurnananda Library Sarasvati Bhavan 30109 η1ac η1pc">η<sub>1</sub></span>)</div>
