   <div class="main">
      <div class="hpmeta">
         <div class="text">
            <div id="hp02_043" class="hp"><span class="number">HP 2.43</span><div class="versdev">
                  <p class="hpvers"> <mark>तत्सिद्धये</mark> <mark>विधानज्ञ</mark><mark>श्चित्रा</mark><mark>न्कुर्वीत</mark> कुम्भकान् ।</p>
                  <p class="hpvers"> <mark>विचित्रकुम्भकाभ्यासा</mark><mark>द्विचित्रां सिद्धिमाप्नुयात्</mark> ॥</p> 
                  </div>
               <div class="versltn">
                  <p class="hpvers"> <mark>tatsiddhaye</mark> <mark>vidhānajña</mark><mark>ś citrā</mark><mark>n kurvīta</mark> kumbhakān /</p>
                  <p class="hpvers"> <mark>vicitrakumbhakābhyāsā</mark><mark>d vicitrāṃ siddhim āpnuyāt</mark> //</p> 
                  </div>
            </div>
            <div class="translation"> In order to achieve that, he who knows [their] methods should perform various retentions.
               As a result of the practice of the various retentions, [the yogi] obtains various
               results. </div>
            <details class="philcomm-d">
               <summary>Philological Commentary</summary>
               <div class="philcomm"> The majority of witnesses, including α2, have a plural subject (<i>vidhānajñāḥ</i>) and verb (<i>kurvanti</i>) in the first hemistich. We have adopted the singular, which is attested by α1, α3 and manuscripts of the <i>Haṭharatnāvalī</i>, because it corresponds with the singular subject of the second hemistich. </div>
            </details>
         </div>
         <div class="crit">
            <div class="apparatus">
