   <div class="main">
      <div class="hpmeta">
         <div class="text">
            <div id="hp03_014" class="hp"><span class="number">HP 3.14</span><div class="versdev">
                  <p class="hpvers"> <mark>महा</mark><mark>क्लेशादयो</mark> <mark>दोषा</mark> <mark>हीयन्ते</mark> मरणादयः ।</p>
                  <p class="hpvers"> महा<mark>मुद्रां</mark> <mark>च</mark> <mark>तेनैव</mark> वदन्ति <mark>विबुधो</mark>त्तमाः ॥ 
                     </p> 
                  </div>
               <div class="versltn">
                  <p class="hpvers"> <mark>mahā</mark><mark>kleśādayo</mark> <mark>doṣā</mark> <mark>hīyante</mark> maraṇādayaḥ /</p>
                  <p class="hpvers"> mahā<mark>mudrāṃ</mark> <mark>ca</mark> <mark>tenaiva</mark> vadanti <mark>vibudho</mark>ttamāḥ // 
                     </p> 
                  </div>
            </div>
            <div class="translation"> Problems such as the great afflictions [and] death and so forth are removed [by it],
               and that is why the most wise call it the `great seal.’ </div>
            <details class="philcomm-d">
               <summary>Philological Commentary</summary>
               <div class="philcomm"> This verse might be explaining the name of <i>mahāmudrā</i> through assonance with <i>mahākleśādayo, doṣā</i> and <i>maraṇādayaḥ</i> in the first line. </div>
            </details>
         </div>
