   <div class="main">
      <div class="hpmeta">
         <div class="text">
            <div id="hp03_042" class="hp"><span class="number">HP 3.42</span><div class="versdev">
                  <p class="hpvers"> नित्यं सोमकला<mark>पूर्णं</mark> शरीरं यस्य <mark>योगिनः</mark> ।</p>
                  <p class="hpvers"> तक्षकेणापि <mark>दष्टस्य</mark> <mark>विषं तस्य न</mark> <mark>सर्पति</mark> ॥<span class="fn" title="βω adds here: tasmād idaṃ prakurvīta nityayuktaḥ samāhitaḥ."><b>*</b></span>
                     </p> 
                  </div>
               <div class="versltn">
                  <p class="hpvers"> nityaṃ somakalā<mark>pūrṇaṃ</mark> śarīraṃ yasya <mark>yoginaḥ</mark> /</p>
                  <p class="hpvers"> takṣakeṇāpi <mark>daṣṭasya</mark> <mark>viṣaṃ tasya na</mark> <mark>sarpati</mark> //<span class="fn" title="βω adds here: tasmād idaṃ prakurvīta nityayuktaḥ samāhitaḥ."><b>*</b></span>
                     </p> 
                  </div>
            </div>
            <div class="translation"> Poison does not enter the yogi whose body is always filled by [nectar from] the digits
               of the moon, even if he is bitten by Takṣaka. </div>
            <details class="philcomm-d">
               <summary>Philological Commentary</summary>
               <div class="philcomm"> In the context of poison, <i>takṣaka</i> refers to one of the three kings of the snakes (<i>nāga</i>), the other two being Śeṣa and Vāsuki (Mani 1975: 782–783). The verb <i>sarpati</i> is well attested by the manuscripts of the <i>Haṭhapradīpikā</i> and testimonia. It can take an object, which in this case is the yogi’s body. </div>
            </details>
         </div>
         <div class="crit">
            <div class="apparatus">
               <h3>Readings</h3>
